# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biathlon-world-championships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biathlon-world-championships/2011-12-biathlon-world-cup] The **2011–12 Biathlon World Cup** was a multi-race tournament over a season of biathlon, organised by the International Biathlon Union.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/2011-12-biathlon-world-cup] The season started on 30 November 2011 in Östersund, Sweden and ended on 18 March 2012 in Khanty-Mansiysk, Russia.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/2011-12-biathlon-world-cup] Below is the IBU World Cup calendar for the 2011–12 season.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/adolf-wiklund-biathlete] He was elected for the Swedish Biathlon Hall of Fame in September 2013.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/adolf-wiklund-biathlete] Wiklund initially began his cross-country skiing career in 1948, having previously worked as a flight technician at a military airfield.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/adolf-wiklund-biathlete] At the first biathlon world championships in Saalfelden in 1958, he won the 20 km distance and was the first biathlon world champion.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/adolf-wiklund-biathlete] He also won a gold medal with the still unofficially held relay.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/adolf-wiklund-biathlete] A year later, he won a silver medal in Courmayeur with the still unofficial relay behind the team from the Soviet Union and finished 9th in the individual over 20 km.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/adolf-wiklund-biathlete] At the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley, he finished 19th and retired the following year.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/adolf-wiklund-biathlete] Wiklund, who lived in Frösön, practiced various sports and he was also a football player, a cross-country, and steeplechase runner.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] At the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin, she won bronze medals in the 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) pursuit and 15 kilometres (9.3 mi) individual; she originally finished fourth in the individual but was promoted when her teammate Olga Pyleva was disqualified after failing a doping test.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] She also won gold, silver, and bronze medals in Olympic relay competitions in 2006, 1998, and 2002, respectively.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] Akhatova also won the gold medals in the mass start at the 2003 World Championship held in Khanty-Mansiysk.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] In 1999 in Oslo, she won the bronze medal, and in 2004 in Oberhof, Germany, she won the silver medal, both over the distance of 15 km.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] She also was part of Russia's winning relay teams at the 2000 and 2003 World Championships.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] After a break in the 2006/07 season, she returned in January 2008.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] At the 2008 World Championships in Östersund, she won the silver medal in the 7.5 kilometres (4.7 mi) sprint and the bronze medal in the subsequent 10 km pursuit.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] On 13 February 2009 the IBU announced that Akhatova, along with teammates Ekaterina Iourieva and Dmitri Yaroshenko, had tested positive for EPO during the World Cup in Östersund.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/albina-akhatova] On 11 August 2009, each was banned for two years.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/aleksandr-elizarov] All results are sourced from the International Biathlon Union.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/aleksandr-privalov] He received a bronze medal at the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/aleksandr-privalov] He received a silver medal at the 1964 Winter Olympics in Innsbruck.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] The first **Biathlon World Championships** (**BWCH**) was held in 1958, with individual and team contests for men.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] The original team event, Team (time), was held for the last time in 1965, to be replaced in 1966 by the team event, Relay (4 × 7.5 km).
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] The number of events has grown significantly over the years.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] Beginning in 1984, women biathletes had their own World Championships, and finally, from 1989, both genders have been participating in joint Biathlon World Championships.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] In 1978 the development was enhanced by the change from the large army rifle calibre to a small bore rifle, while the range to the target was reduced from 150 to 50 meters.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] The Biathlon World Championships of the season takes place during February or March.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] Some years it has been necessary to schedule parts of the Championships at other than the main venue because of weather and/or snow conditions.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] Full, joint Biathlon World Championships have never been held in Olympic Winter Games seasons.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] Biathlon World Championships in non-IOC events, however, have been held in Olympic seasons.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] In 2005, the then new event of Mixed Relay (two legs done by women, two legs by men) was arranged separately from the ordinary Championships.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] Numbers in brackets denotes number of victories in corresponding disciplines.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] Boldface denotes record number of victories.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] This event was first held unofficially in 1965.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] It was a success, and replaced the team competition as an official event in 1966.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] The times of the top 3 athletes from each country in the 20 km individual were added together (in 1958 the top 4).
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] This event, a patrol race, was held from 1989 to 1998.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p01] From 1989–93 the distance of this event was 20 km, while from 1994–98, the distance was 10 km.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] In 2003, the leg distance was set to 6 km.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] This event was first held in 2005, at the Biathlon World Cup finals in Khanty-Mansiysk.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] In 2005–20, the women biathletes did the first two legs and the men did the following two (except 2006 when sequence was woman–man–woman–man), the women's ski legs were 6 km each while men ski legs were 7.5 km each (except 2005, 2006 and 2020 when ski legs were 6 km each for all relay members).
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] In 2021, the starting gender became the result of an alternation: for the first time, men opened the relay and women closed it.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] Since then, this sequence alternates for each following edition.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] The distance skied became the same for all genders and depending on the one running the first leg (7.5 km if men run first, 6 km if women do), but in 2024 it became 6 km for every relay member no matter who runs first leg.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] Each team consists of two members - man and woman.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] The first of the team members runs the first and third legs (3 km each), the other team member – the second and fourth legs (3 km and 4.5 km respectively).
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] In 2019 and 2020 the women biathletes started single mixed relay and the men biathletes finished it, but in 2021 this order was reversed.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] Since then, this order alternates for each following edition.
[src:biathlon-world-championships/biathlon-world-championships-p02] Boldface denotes active biathletes and highest medal count among all biathletes (including these who not included in these tables) per type.
